04455nam a22006735i 9780231504676DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979831684  a97802315046767 a10.7312/disc110342doi  a(DE-B1597)458804  a(OCoLC)51606513  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0300002bisacsh04a324.2731 aDisch, Lisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Tyranny of the Two-Party System /cLisa Disch. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (172 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPower, Conflict, and Democracy: American Politics Into the 21st Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Tyranny of the Two-Party System -- t1. The Politics of Electoral Fusion, 1994–1997 -- t2. The Politics of the Two-Party System -- t3. The Two-Party System: Genealogy of a Catchphrase -- t4. The Two-Party System and the Ideology of Process -- t5. Oppositional Democracy and the Promise of Electoral Fusion -- tConclusion: Against the Tyranny of the Two-Party System -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe closely contested presidential election of 2000, which many analysts felt was decided by voters for the Green Party, cast a spotlight on a structural contradiction of American politics. Critics charged that Green Party voters inadvertently contributed to the election of a conservative Republican president because they chose to "vote their conscience" rather than "choose between two evils." But why this choice of two? Is the two-party system of Democrats and Republicans an immutable and indispensable aspect of our democracy? Lisa Disch maintains that it is not. There is no constitutional warrant for two parties, and winner-take-all elections need not set third parties up to fail. She argues that the two-party system as we know it dates only to the twentieth century and that it thwarts democracy by wasting the votes and silencing the voices of dissenters. The Tyranny of the Two-Party System reexamines a once popular nineteenth-century strategy called fusion, in which a dominant-party candidate ran on the ballots of both the established party and a third party. In the nineteenth century fusion made possible something that many citizens wish were possible today: to register a protest vote that counts and that will not throw the election to the establishment candidate they least prefer. The book concludes by analyzing the 2000 presidential election as an object lesson in the tyranny of the two-party system and with suggestions for voting experiments to stimulate participation and make American democracy responsive to a broader range of citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / National.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/disc1103440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231504676423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231504676/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK